entry.title: Prepare to convert SBThreatType to an enum class in /components/subresource_filter
entry.content:
It's somewhat difficult to log an SBThreatType as an UMA histogram since

we don't have a kMaxValue. We can't simply add a kMaxValue because

SBThreatType is an enum instead of enum class, and we'd be exposing a

constant safe_browsing::kMaxValue. This CL prepares to convert

SBThreatType to an enum class in /components/subresource_filter.



That requires two changes:



- SBThreatType is no longer implicitly convertible to int, so we will

need a few static casts



- SBThreatType values are now in the namespace

safe_browsing::SBThreatType instead of just safe_browsing. In some

places this is fixed by adding the new namespace, and in some places

with a "using enum" declaration. We can't just add a "using enum" for

all usages of SBThreatType because "using enum" would declare a

constant kMaxValue. So "using enum" is only used when many

SBThreatType constants are used, and in as narrow a scope as possible.



This CL was uploaded by git cl split.

entry.title: [UNO] Maintain account consistency Pre Chrome Sign in
entry.content:
When explicit browser sign in is enabled and the user is not signed in

to chrome, account consistency works in the following manner:

- First, refresh tokens that do not have a valid counter account in the

cookie are revoked.

- Then if needed, the cookie is updated to remove accounts that do not

have a refresh token. This is possible:

(1) If the user has signed out from chrome layer while being offline.

(2) If an account is moved from a profile to another as part of the

Sign in interception flows or as a result merge sync data flow.



First step has been implemented on previous CLs. This CL implements

the second step to update the accounts in the cookie.



In case the first account in the cookie doesn't have a refresh token,

the reconcilor would only perform a logout if the account is valid to

avoid reordering accounts on the web during an active session. If the

account is invalid, we would rather reorder than logout all accounts.

entry.title: Fenced frames: Revoke network access for partition nonce [1/N]
entry.content:
This CL creates an IPC on NetworkContext that is called from window.fence.disableUntrustedNetwork to register a given partition nonce in a new data structure in the NetworkContext, which is later used to deny network access.



Future CLs will make checks against the data structure more robust (e.g., cancel redirects in addition to just failing to start requests),

actually delete nonces that are no longer needed (when the

FencedFrameProperties is destructed), and restore the data structure

upon network service crash/restart.



This CL temporarily moves WPT that exercise

window.fence.disableUntrustedNetwork from external to internal WPT,

because we need to be able to use remote context (which relies on

network access) even after network is revoked. In the medium term

we will do this with a new testdriver API, but adding a testdriver

API requires a process that we don't want to block this CL on.



See this implementation design doc for more context:

https://docs.google.com/document/d/1JnwuFl84P5jR_9PkpM68WdCD63UerKxWm-v4XXj2sRc/edit#heading=h.bat9awopsp53

entry.title: aura window capture: Take capture locks for aura windows
entry.content:
Currently, windows are assumed to have their ui compositor visible and

drawing in NativeDesktopMediaList. If native occlusion affecting the

compositor is enabled, then this may not be true and those windows may

not be drawn. If the windows are never drawn, then we cannot take

a snapshot of them for the thumbnail.



This CL takes a video capture lock for the WindowTreeHost corresponding

to each aura window. This is required to make sure those windows are

visible so they can have thumbnails captured of them.

entry.title: Speculative fix: Finish the previous warm-up before proceeding to the next warm-up
entry.content:
One of the crashes contained the following stack trace.



ServiceWorkerVersion::DidEnsureLiveRegistrationForStartWorker

ServiceWorkerContextWrapper::MaybeProcessPendingWarmUpRequest

ServiceWorkerContextWrapper::DidWarmUpServiceWorker

ServiceWorkerVersion::FinishStartWorker

ServiceWorkerVersion::OnTimeoutTimer



This means that, when the warm-up was timed out for some reason, it

tries to abort starting worker with FinishStartWorker, and it calls

DidWarmUpServiceWorker. At this moment, the service worker keeps

kStarting state.



Even though the previous service worker is not completely stopped, and

the status is still kStarting, DidWarmUpServiceWorker directly starts

the next warm-up request. Eventually,

DidEnsureLiveRegistrationForStartWorker is called, and it fails with

`CHECK(IsWarmingUp() || IsWarmedUp())`.



To fix this problem, this CL intends to run the following

`embedded_worker_->Stop();` in ServiceWorkerVersion::OnTimeoutTimer()

before proceeding to the next warm-up so that the running state becomes

kStopping before processing the next warm-up request.



```

FinishStartWorker(blink::ServiceWorkerStatusCode::kErrorTimeout);

if (running_status() == blink::EmbeddedWorkerStatus::kStarting) {

embedded_worker_->Stop();

}

```



The above description explains the following 2 changes in this CL. The

following functions can be called directly from

ServiceWorkerVersion::OnTimeoutTimer before this CL.



- ServiceWorkerContextWrapper::DidFindRegistrationForWarmUp

- ServiceWorkerContextWrapper::DidWarmUpServiceWorker



The change in ServiceWorkerVersion::OnStoppedInternal is a speculative

fix for https://crbug.com/328740460 which

ServiceWorkerVersion::worker_host_ becomes null sometimes I'm still not

sure how this can happen, but from the crash trend, this crash seems to

be relevant to `sw_warm_up_on_idle_timeout` feature parameter.

we take a video capture lock, the occlusion state of the root window is

unaffected. However, the intent of the video capture lock is to capture

an otherwise not visible window. If the occlusion state is not set to

visible, it can affect the content of the window and hence the video

capture.



This CL forces the root window to be visible if there is at least one

video capture lock.

entry.title: Prepare to convert SBThreatType to an enum class in /ios/chrome/browser/web/model
entry.content:
It's somewhat difficult to log an SBThreatType as an UMA histogram since

we don't have a kMaxValue. We can't simply add a kMaxValue because

SBThreatType is an enum instead of enum class, and we'd be exposing a

constant safe_browsing::kMaxValue. This CL prepares to convert

SBThreatType to an enum class in /ios/chrome/browser/web/model.



That requires two changes:



- SBThreatType is no longer implicitly convertible to int, so we will

need a few static casts



- SBThreatType values are now in the namespace

safe_browsing::SBThreatType instead of just safe_browsing. In some

places this is fixed by adding the new namespace, and in some places

with a "using enum" declaration. We can't just add a "using enum" for

all usages of SBThreatType because "using enum" would declare a

constant kMaxValue. So "using enum" is only used when many

SBThreatType constants are used, and in as narrow a scope as possible.



This CL was uploaded by git cl split.

entry.title: Implement BackgroundResponseProcessor for script streaming
entry.content:
This CL introduces a new feature param "background-response-processor"

for the BackgroundResourceFetch feature.

If this param is enabled, ResourceLoader::RequestAsynchronously()

will call Resource::MaybeCreateBackgroundResponseProcessor() method

when `loader_` is a BackgroundURLLoader. And if the method returns a

BackgroundResponseProcessor, it will be set to the BackgroundURLLoader.

The BackgroundURLLoader will call MaybeStartProcessingResponse() method

of the BackgroundResponseProcessor when the response is received

(https://crrev.com/c/5321069 implemented this logic).



This CL also implements the MaybeCreateBackgroundResponseProcessor()

method of ScriptResource class. This method creates a

BackgroundResourceScriptStreamer, and returns the

BackgroundResponseProcessor of the BackgroundResourceScriptStreamer.



When BackgroundResourceScriptStreamer::BackgroundResponseProcessor's

MaybeCreateBackgroundResponseProcessor() is called on the background

thread:

1. BackgroundResponseProcessor performs the following checks to see if

the response can be parsed by ScriptStreamingTask of V8:

- If the script is for module script, the mime type must be a valid

mime type of JavaScript.

- The passed `cached_metadata` must not contain code cache.

- The encoding of the script must be windows-1252, ISO-8859-1,

US-ASCII, or UTF-8 which are supported by V8's parser.

- The body size must be larger than 4 bytes.

2. If the check can be performed synchronously:

- If the response is eligible, create a ScriptDecoder to decode the

script in a background thread and start a ScriptStreamingTask in

a separate background thread. And the method returns true.

- Otherwise, returns false.

3. If the check can't be performed synchronously, the method returns

true. Then waits for the body data and runs the check again.

- If the response is eligible, create a ScriptDecoder to decode the

script in a background thread and start a ScriptStreamingTask in

a separate background thread.

- Otherwise, it calls DidFinishBackgroundResponseProcessor() of

BackgroundResponseProcessor::Client.

4. When the ScriptStreamingTask finishes, and a ScriptDecoder finishes

decoding the script, BackgroundResponseProcessor calls

DidFinishBackgroundResponseProcessor() of

BackgroundResponseProcessor::Client.



If MayaCreateBackgroundResponseProcessor() returns false,

BackgroundURLLoader quickly calls ResourceLoader::DidReceiveResponse().

Otherwise, it waits until DidFinishBackgroundResponseProcessor() is

called, and then calls ResourceLoader::DidReceiveResponse(). And after

the resource request finishes, ScriptStreamer::TakeFrom() will be called

to take the BackgroundResourceScriptStreamer of the ScriptResource.



The data flow diagram can be found in the design doc:

https://docs.google.com/document/d/11cEc3KFpM7NwMMY9OkIUkIg5vGisNTXvzLZMgwBM-BM/edit#heading=h.19p27l1u1z0z

entry.title: Don't connect Pages with fake main RemoteFrame to related pages
entry.content:
With RenderDocument, on same-site main frame navigations, we create

the new RenderFrame by creating a new WebViewImpl which has a ‚Äúfake‚Äù

RemoteFrame, and the new RenderFrame as the fake RemoteFrame‚Äôs

provisional RenderFrame. Note that we need a ‚Äúfake‚Äù RemoteFrame as a

placeholder for the new WebViewImpl‚Äôs main frame because we can‚Äôt put

the provisional LocalFrame there (it will be treated as an ‚Äúactive‚Äù main frame if we do so).



Because the fake RemoteFrame will be on a new Page, iterating through pages with RelatedPages() might return the "fake" Page while it's

still provisional (still has the main frame as the fake RemoteFrame

and the real LocalFrame is still provisional). This is problematic

in FrameTree::FindFrameForNavigationInternal() because that might

try to navigate the fake RemoteFrame, which will crash when trying

to send the navigate mojo call to the non-existent browser counterpart.

See test at http/tests/workers/worker-invalid-context.html.



This CL makes it so that we won't connect those pages while they

still use the fake main RemoteFrame to avoid exposing it while it's

still fake / provisional. This is done by moving the connecting of

RelatedPages to SetMainFrame(), which we'll skip if the main frame

is a fake RemoteFrame. When the provisional LocalFrame gets swapped

in during commit later on, the function will be called again and

we'll connect the page to its related pages at that timing.



Bug: 936696

entry.title: [URL] Ensure correct handling of path-only non-special URLs
entry.content:
Prevent a path-only non-special URL, "non-special:/.//path", from

ending up as "non-special://path", instead of "non-special:/.//path".



Note that a leading "/." should be *prepended* before the path so the

path part, "//path", shouldn't be considered as a URL's host part.



Previously, these URLs might incorrectly lose the leading "./" part, or

forget to add "./".



This implements the URL Standard: 4.5 serializing:



https://url.spec.whatwg.org/#url-serializing



> 3. If url‚Äôs host is null, url does not have an opaque path, url‚Äôs

> path‚Äôs size is greater than 1, and url‚Äôs path[0] is the empty string,

> then append U+002F (/) followed by U+002E (.) to output.



Examples:



> const url = new URL("git:/.//a");

> url.href

=> should be "git:/.//a", instead of "git://a".



> const url = new URL("git:/");

> url.pathname = "//a";

> url.href

=> should be "git:/.//a", instead of "git://a".



> const url = new URL("", "git:/.//a");

> url.href

=> should be "git:/.//a", instead of "git://a".



> const url = new URL("..//b", "git:/.//a");

> url.href

=> should be "git:/.//b", instead of "git://b"



> const url = new URL("../b", "git:/.//a");

> url.href

=> should be "git:/b", instead of "git:/./b"



This CL also fixes the following case which replaces pathname with an

empty path.



> const url = new URL("git:/");

> url.pathname = "";

> url.href

=> should be "git:/", instead of "git:".

> url.pathname

=> should be "/", instead of "".



The URL Standard (https://url.spec.whatwg.org/#dom-url-pathname) defines

the behavior of this case. Unfortunately, it is not easy to understand

why url.pathname ends up as "/" in this case since the URL Standard

appear cryptic. Please read the URL Standard carefully to understand

that. I omit my understanding here.



Tests:



While the WPT URL tests provide good coverage for these scenarios, I

also added some minimal unit tests for additional assurance.

entry.title: Prepare to convert SBThreatType to an enum class in /chrome/browser/preloading/prefetch/no_state_prefetch
entry.content:
It's somewhat difficult to log an SBThreatType as an UMA histogram since

we don't have a kMaxValue. We can't simply add a kMaxValue because

SBThreatType is an enum instead of enum class, and we'd be exposing a

constant safe_browsing::kMaxValue. This CL prepares to convert

SBThreatType to an enum class in /chrome/browser/preloading/prefetch/no_state_prefetch.



That requires two changes:



- SBThreatType is no longer implicitly convertible to int, so we will

need a few static casts



- SBThreatType values are now in the namespace

safe_browsing::SBThreatType instead of just safe_browsing. In some

places this is fixed by adding the new namespace, and in some places

with a "using enum" declaration. We can't just add a "using enum" for

all usages of SBThreatType because "using enum" would declare a

constant kMaxValue. So "using enum" is only used when many

SBThreatType constants are used, and in as narrow a scope as possible.



This CL was uploaded by git cl split.
